## Guide-level explanation

### The core insight

AWS SSM Parameter Store stores `/app/database-url`. HashiCorp Vault stores `secret/redis/password`. Kubernetes Secrets namespace by key. Every major provider independently converged on the same structure — hierarchical paths, one value per addressable unit — because that shape is what per-parameter access control, auditing, and rotation actually require.

penv's filesystem layout mirrors this exactly. A local penv tree and a provider path are two serializations of the same logical record `(environment, path, name)`. Because the shapes match, switching providers is a configuration change rather than an application rewrite.

This is not file-based routing applied to config for aesthetic reasons. It is a structural match to what `provider: vault` or `provider: aws-ssm` already looks like on the other end.

### What it looks like

```
project-root/
├── package.json
├── penv.config.ts          # config: environments, providers, name mapping
└── .penv/
    ├── schema.ts           # one Zod schema — runtime validation + type inference
    │
    ├── database-url                      # unscoped default value
    ├── database-url.production.enc       # production override, encrypted
    ├── database-url.json                 # per-parameter meta (one file)
    │
    ├── app/
    │   ├── jwt-secret.development
    │   ├── jwt-secret.production.enc
    │   └── jwt-secret.json
    │
    ├── redis/
    │   ├── host.production
    │   ├── password.production.enc
    │   └── password.json
    │
    └── stripe/
        ├── secret-key.production.enc
        └── secret-key.json
```

Each value file contains exactly one value. Each parameter has at most one meta file. Nothing is a proprietary database — everything is inspectable with ordinary filesystem tools.

### The five-minute value moment

The fastest way to demonstrate penv's worth is not to ask a team to restructure their filesystem first. It is to point `penv doctor` at their existing provider instance and their local configuration and produce one report of everything that has drifted:

```
$ penv doctor

✓ Schema valid
⚠ Missing parameter         redis.password         (in schema, absent for production)
⚠ Weak secret               app.jwt-secret         (18 chars, schema requires ≥32)
⚠ Unused parameter          LEGACY_API_KEY         (present, not in schema)
⚠ Drifted from provider     stripe.secret-key      (local ≠ vault:secret/production)
⚠ Unscoped fallback in use  api-url                (production resolving to default)
✓ Encryption enabled
✓ Provider                  vault
```

The filesystem model is the *payoff* for teams who want to act on what doctor finds — not a precondition for getting value from penv.

### Runtime access

```ts
import { env } from "penv";

env.databaseUrl;          // fully typed, inferred from schema.ts
env.app.jwtSecret;        // nested, matching the namespace hierarchy
env.require("jwt-secret"); // throws with a clear message if absent
```

Adopting penv does not require changing existing application code that reads `process.env` — a compatibility layer populates it. New code can use the typed surface.

