## Rationale and alternatives

**Why filesystem-native rather than one structured file (SOPS-style)?** A single encrypted structured file (SOPS) gets per-value encryption without the many-files cost. penv chooses per-file storage because the filesystem *is* the structural match to provider path models — the isomorphism that makes provider switching a config change is the point, and it is weaker when the local representation is one opaque blob. The tradeoff is accepted knowingly; SOPS remains the better choice for teams that want per-value encryption without restructuring.

**Why not just use Infisical / Doppler?** Those are the closest actual competitors — dev-to-prod secret platforms with CLIs and provider sync. penv differs on three axes: it is filesystem-native and inspectable rather than platform-hosted; it provides typed runtime access inferred from one Zod schema; and it targets provider *portability* rather than lock-in to one vendor's platform. A team happy inside a hosted platform is not penv's target.

**Why not extend `.env` with a convention?** Conventions on top of a flat file cannot deliver per-parameter ACLs or independent rotation, because the unit of the file is the file. The addressable unit has to change for those capabilities to exist at all.

**Why so narrow a target market?** Excluding solo developers and t3-env users is deliberate. penv cannot out-compete purpose-built tools on onboarding speed, and pretending otherwise produced the original, weaker positioning. The honest target is teams already running a real secret manager who maintain the local↔production translation by hand. Whether that market is large enough is an open commercial question this RFC does not resolve — it is a demand question, answered by customer conversations, not by design.

